## Violation C2: No Database-Level Constraints for Business Rules

**Files:** [schema.prisma](file:///d:/Projects/sukoon/backend/prisma/schema.prisma)

Several business rules exist only in service-layer code but have **no database-level enforcement**:

| Business Rule | Where it's enforced | What's missing |
|---|---|---|
| "A user can only have one active Pomodoro session" | [pomodoro-sessions.service.ts:17-22](file:///d:/Projects/sukoon/backend/src/modules/pomodoro/sessions/pomodoro-sessions.service.ts#L17-L22) — `if (activeSession) throw` | No unique partial index on `(userId) WHERE isCompleted = false` |
| "Tag name is unique per user" | [tags.service.ts:15-18](file:///d:/Projects/sukoon/backend/src/modules/task/tags/tags.service.ts#L15-L18) — `if (exists) throw` | No `@@unique([userId, name])` on Tag model |
| "Pomodoro duration must be positive" | Nowhere | No `CHECK (duration > 0)` constraint |
| "A task can only be in trash once (deletedAt not null)" | Implicit | No validation that prevents soft-deleting an already-soft-deleted task |

### 💡 The Lesson — Defense in Depth
Think of consistency like airport security: you don't rely on just one checkpoint. You have:
1. **Application layer** (Zod validation, service checks) — the first gate.
2. **Database layer** (constraints, unique indexes, CHECK constraints) — the last gate.

Right now, Sukoon has the first gate only. If anyone bypasses the service layer (a bug, a direct SQL query, a migration script), invalid data goes straight into the database.

