## Violation I2: `addTagToTask` — Three Reads Before One Write

**File:** [tags.repository.ts](file:///d:/Projects/sukoon/backend/src/modules/task/tags/tags.repository.ts#L117-L153)

```typescript
async addTagToTask(tagId: number, taskId: number, userId: number) {
    // Read 1: Check tag exists and belongs to user
    const tag = await prisma.tag.findUnique({ where: { id: tagId, userId } });
    // Read 2: Check task exists and belongs to user
    const task = await prisma.task.findUnique({ where: { id: taskId, userId } });
    if (!tag || !task) throw new Error("...");

    // Read 3: Check if tag is already on this task
    const existing = await prisma.taskTag.findUnique({
        where: { taskId_tagId: { taskId, tagId } },
    });
    if (existing) throw new Error("Tag already added to this task");

    // Write: Actually add the tag
    return await prisma.taskTag.create({ data: { taskId, tagId } });
}
```

### 🔴 The Problem
Between Read 3 (checking if tag-task link exists) and the Write (creating it), another request can insert the same link. The composite primary key `@@id([taskId, tagId])` on `TaskTag` will catch this with a **P2002 unique constraint error** — but the code doesn't handle it gracefully. The user gets a raw Prisma error instead of a clean message.

### 💡 The Isolation Lesson
The more **reads** you do before a **write**, the wider the "window of vulnerability" for race conditions. Each read creates an assumption about the world ("this tag exists," "this link doesn't exist yet"), and by the time the write happens, those assumptions might be stale.

